Workshop on Experimental Design & Data Analysis

Topic: Generalized Additive Mixed Models

Priscila Lopez-Beltran forcada, Ph.D.

Updated on July, 2023

In this workshop, we will learn how to analyze time series data. to exemplify this, we will be analyzing pupillometry data.


First, what is time series data?

Time course refers to the evolution of a measurement over time. Time series refers to data that form a sequence ordered in time. Therefore, you do a time course experiment and you analyze time series. In our case, pupillometry is considered time series data because data on pupil dilation are collected continuously as the experiment unfolds such that we can obtain a dynamic, continuous measurement of pupil size over a period of time.

The method used to analyze time series data that we will learn in todays session is called Generalized Additive Mixed Models (GAMMs). A GAMM can be seen as a regression model which is able to model non-linear patterns in the data.

For example, we see below that a regression line is unable to capture the non-linear nature of the F2 trajectory.



Let us refer to the slopes and intercepts of linear regression models as parametric terms. GAMMs differ from traditional linear regression models by allowing smooth terms alongside parametric terms. Smooth terms are extremely flexible, that is how they can account for non-linear patterns.

Similar to linear mixed effects models, GAMMs incorporate random effects. These can be random intercepts and random slopes. However, GAMMs also offer a third option: random smooths.

Random smooths are similar to random slopes, but they are more flexible than the latter: while random slopes can only capture by-group variation in linear effects, random smooths can also deal with by-group variation in non-linear effects.



GAMMs in practice

The experiment: The Spanish Subjunctive

In Spanish, mood selection is primarily lexically conditioned, which entails that a number of verbs (aka governors) govern use of the subjunctive and indicative moods A subset of these governors are non-variable, meaning that they select the subjunctive 100% of the times (e.g., querer). This experiment investigates heritage speakers of Spanish sensitivity to this lexical constraint.

Lexical Conditioning Experiment

1. Condition Non-variable Subjunctive (NVS) consists of a non-variable governor (in bold) followed by a subordinate verb in the subjunctive (in italics).

2. Condition Non-variable Indicative (NVI) is comprised of a non-variable governor (in bold) followed by a subordinate verb in the indicative (in italics).



Hypothesis Condition NVI will elicit higher pupillary dilation in participants if they are sensitive to the lexical constraint that non-variable governors select the subjunctive categorically (100%).

Specifying a GAMMs model

The main packages we will be using for GAMMs are mgcv to design models and itsadug to plot results.

After we load in the the data, we must make sure that all categorical variables are factors, otherwise the model wont run. Finally, we design our model.

We will use the bam() function to create our model. This will take approximately 3-5 minutes using a MacBook Pro with Apple M1 Max chip and 32GB of RAM.

model_NV <- bam(corrected_pupil_size ~ condition # fixed effects
             + s(bin, by = condition, k = 20) # smooth for time by condition
             + s(gaze_x, gaze_y) # smooth for gaze position
             + s(bin, participant, bs = 'fs', m = 1, k = 10) # factor smooth for time by participant
             + s(bin, item, bs = 'fs', m = 1, k = 10) # factor smooth for time by item
             , family = "scat" # t-distribution, as assumed in regression
             , data = target_NV # data
             , method = "fREML" # smoothing parameter estimation method fast REML
             , discrete = TRUE) # will help the model converge faster

summary(model_NV)

Parametric coefficients

These are our fixed effects. As in regular linear regression, the intercept is the value of the dependent variable when all numerical predictors are equal to 0 and nominal variables are at their reference level. In this case, the intercept represents the value of the prediction Condition Non-Variable Indicative (NVI). We observe that for condition NVS, the pupillary dilation is -7.11 millimeters smaller than for NVI, which supports our hypothesis.

Smooth terms

1. edf

The edf value is indicative of the amount of non-linearity of the smooth. If the edf value for a certain smooth is (close to) 1, this means that the pattern is (close to) linear, while a value greater than 1 indicates that the pattern is more complex (i.e.non-linear).

2. Ref.df and F

The Ref.df value is the reference number of degrees of freedom used for hypothesis testing (on the basis of the associated F-value)

3. p-value

The p-value associated with each smooth indicates only if a smooth term is significantly different from 0. In this case, all variables are highly significantly different from 0. If we focus on the first two lines of coefficients, which are those of interest to us, we see that the p-value for NVI is much higher than for NVS, indicating a higher difference from 0 (in pupillary dilation) in the former.

Goodness-of-fit measures

The Adjusted R2 represents the amount of variance explained by the regression, while the Deviance Explained is a generalization of R2 and will be very similar to the actual R2 value. Both of them are pretty good in this model. Consider that with time series data, especially when we try to account for as much variability as possible, it is very common to see deviance explained values that are quite low (14.4% here). There is nothing inherently wrong with this, it is just a by-product of the type of data and models were are using.


Significance testing - Visualization

In GAMMs, significant p-values dont really tell us much. We only know that both conditions (NVI & NVS) are significantly different from 0. We can infer which one is more different (higher p-value), but in order to actually assess significance, we need to visualize the results.

In order to better understand the plots we are about to produce, a brief explanation of how time series data is binned is necessary.
The recording frequency of many eye trackers is not now up to 1000Hz, which means that 1000 samples (i.e., data points) are recorded per second. Most often, we dont need millisecond precision in our timevariable,and so binning the data helps reduce the data file size.
Thus, by binning the data, we are going to create artificial breaks in the data to create the BINS. For examples, the figure below represents for 30 ms of data. I am going to use 10 ms bins, which means that every 10 ms, data will be grouped together into a bin.



Now, we can visualize the smooths for NVI and NVS. On the Y axis we have pupillary dilation, and on the X axis we have time. We see that NVI elicited higher dilation than NVS starting around time bin 20 (~400 ms into the target period).

In all, by interpreting the model and the graphs produced, we can determine that there is a significant difference between conditions which suggests that participants were sensitive to the lexical constraints of non-variable governors for mood selection.

Significance testing - Binary difference smooths

Another possibility for significance testing is building a model with binary difference smooths. These model the difference between the two original smooths. Subsequently, we can assess if this difference smooth is found to be significant from the model itself.

To fit this new model, we first have to create a dummy variable. Below, we create the variable IsInd (Is Indicative) where the reference value 0 = Subjunctive and 1 = Indicative

target_NV$IsInd <- (target_NV$condition == "NVI")*1


Then we specify a model a with smooths which models the difference between the levels of the dummy variable

model_Binary <- bam(corrected_pupil_size ~
                             + s(bin, k = 20) # ref. level = subjunctive
                             + s(bin, by = IsInd, k = 20) # indicative - subjunctive
                             + s(gaze_x, gaze_y)
                             + s(bin, participant, bs = 'fs', m = 1, k = 10)
                             + s(bin, item, bs = 'fs', m = 1, k = 10)
                             , family = "scat"
                             , data = target_NV
                             , method = "fREML"
                             , discrete = TRUE)
summary(model_Binary)

Interactions with categorical variables

To explore interactions between categorical variables in GAMMs, first visualize the interaction and then test it.

1. Visualization

Well need to create a new crossover factor that contains all possible permutations between the two variables of interest. For example if we have:

  • Condition
    • NVS
    • NVI
  • Regularity
    • Regular
    • Irregular

The crossover factor CondReg yields four levels: + NVS Regular + NVS Irregular + NVI Regular + NVI Irregular

We will now create a model with the crossover factor CondReg in order to be able to visualize the smooths for each level. According to the extant literature, our prediction would be that in the subjunctive, irregular subordinate verbs would be more costly to process.



Lets plot the smooths:

plot_smooth(model_CondReg, view = "bin", plot_all = c("CondReg"), 
            rm.ranef = TRUE, rug = FALSE, shade = FALSE, se = 0, lwd = 8,
            main = "Pupillary Response Smooths based on Fitted Values \nNon-variable Governors",
            xlab = "Time Bin (20ms per bin)",
            ylab = "Corrected Pupil Size",
            hide.label = T,
            family = "serif")

2. Significance Testing

We will now create a binary difference smooth model that will actually enable us to statistically test the interaction between Condition and Regularity.

We will be creating two models with different reference levels so that we can explore all levels of the interaction we are interested in.

# Create binary variables by Regularity
target_NV$IsInd <- (target_NV$condition == "NVI")*1 # Ref level subjunctive
target_NV$IsReg <- (target_NV$regularity == "regular")*1 # Ref level irregular
target_NV$IsIndReg <- (target_NV$condition == "NVI" & target_NV$regularity == "regular")*1 # NVS Reg - NVS Irreg


First, we create a model with Subjunctive Irregular as reference level:

model_Binary_SI <- bam(corrected_pupil_size ~
                                + s(bin, k = 20) # Ref.level: Sub.Irreg
                                + s(bin, by = IsInd, k = 20) # Ind.Irreg - Sub.Irreg
                                + s(bin, by = IsReg, k = 20) # Sub.Reg - Sub.Irreg
                                + s(bin, by = IsIndReg, k = 20) # 4-way interaction
                                + s(gaze_x, gaze_y)
                                + s(bin, participant, bs = 'fs', m = 1, k = 10)
                                + s(bin, item, bs = 'fs', m = 1, k = 10)
                                , family = "scat"
                                , data = target_NV
                                , method = "fREML"
                                , discrete = TRUE)

summary(model_Binary_SI)

Second, we create a model with Indicative Regular as reference level:

target_NV$IsSub <- (target_NV$condition == "NVS")*1 # indicative as reference level
target_NV$IsIrreg <- (target_NV$regularity == "irregular")*1 # regular as reference level
target_NV$IsSubIrreg <- (target_NV$condition == "NVS" & target_NV$regularity == "irregular")*1 # NVI Irreg - NVI Reg
model_Binary_IR <- bam(corrected_pupil_size ~
                                + s(bin, k = 20) # Ref.level: Ind.Reg
                                + s(bin, by = IsSub, k = 20) # Sub.Reg - Ind.Reg
                                + s(bin, by = IsIrreg, k = 20) # Ind.Irreg - Ind.Reg
                                + s(bin, by = IsSubIrreg, k = 20) # 4-way interaction
                                + s(gaze_x, gaze_y)
                                + s(bin, participant, bs = 'fs', m = 1, k = 10)
                                + s(bin, item, bs = 'fs', m = 1, k = 10)
                                , family = "scat"
                                , data = target_NV
                                , method = "fREML"
                                , discrete = TRUE)

Interactions with continuous variables

When fitting a model to examine an interaction with a continuous variable we need tensor product smooths, rather than binary difference smooths.

For instance, to explore the effects of Proficiency (Picture Naming RTs) on Condition in GAMMs, the effect needs to be modeled as an interaction with time, given that time series data is being analyzed.

Thus, the resulting non-linear interaction accounts for changes in pupil size caused by proficiency on condition over time.

Visualization

In the case of interactions with continuous variables, visualization is essential to understand the results because it is the only method used to determine significance.

To visualize a two-dimensional pattern such as the effect of proficiency on condition over time, contour plots based on the models predictions have to be plotted.

Here, the color bands represents the range of values of the dependent variable, in this case the difference in pupillary response between conditions (i.e., NIV minus NVS), the closer to red, the greater the difference.

The highlighted areas in the plot indicate where there was a significant effect of the independent variable (y-axis) on the dependent variable, and the x-axis shows the time course of the effect.

In addition, to further interpret the results observed, one-dimensional difference smooths can also be plotted in order to assess the magnitude, duration and time-course of the effects.
